Context: The \textalpha{}4\textbeta{}2 nAChR exists in two stoichiometries: HS (\textalpha{}4)\textsubscript{2}(\textbeta{}2)\textsubscript{3} and LS (\textalpha{}4)\textsubscript{3}(\textbeta{}2)\textsubscript{2}, with the LS stoichiometry featuring an α4-α4 interface that serves as an operational agonist binding site, targeted by ligands like NS9283 which potentiates agonist responses.

Consider the following analogues designed by taking into account NS9283's interactions in the \textalpha{}4-\textalpha{}4 binding site:

\begin{itemize} \item NS9283: N#Cc3cccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)c3 \item Comp-1: c3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3 \item Comp-2: c3cncc(c2noc(c1cccnc1)n2)c3 \item Comp-3: O=N+c1ccccc1c3nc(c2cccnc2)no3 \item Comp-4: O=N+c3cccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)c3 \item Comp-5 O=N+c3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3 \item Comp-6: Fc3cccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)c3 \item Comp-7: Fc3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3F \item Comp-8: c3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)nc3 \item Comp-9: c3cncc(c2noc(c1ccncc1)n2)c3 \item Comp-10: N#Cc3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3 \item Comp-11: Fc3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3 \item Comp-12: Fc3cc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc(F)c3F \item Comp-13: Fc3cc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)c(F)c(F)c3F \item Comp-14: O=N+c3cc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)ccc3F \item Comp-15: O=N+c3ccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)cc3F \item Comp-16 Fc1ccncc1c3nc(c2cccnc2)no3 \item Comp-17: O=C(O-)c3cccc(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)c3 \item Comp-18: O=CN3CCCC(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)C3 \item Comp-19: CC(=O)N3CCCC(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)C3 \item Comp-20: O=CN3CCC(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)CC3 \item Comp-21: CC(=O)N3CCC(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)CC3 \item Comp-22: C3=C(c2nc(c1cccnc1)no2)CCCC3 \item Comp-23: N#Cc3cccc(c2nc(C1CCCCC1)no2)c3 \item Comp-24: N#Cc3cccc(c2nc(N1CCCCC1)no2)c3 \item Comp-25: N#Cc3cccc(c2nc(c1ccoc1)no2)c3 \item Comp-26: N#Cc3cccc(c2nc(c1cccc(C(=O)O)c1)no2)c3 \end{itemize}

From these compounds, the following screening was obtained by co-applying \qty{10}{\micro\Molar} of each compound with \qty{30}{\micro\Molar} ACh to \textit{Xenopus laevis} oocytes expressing LS \textalpha{}4\textbeta{}2. The results are the responses normalized to the response to ACh \qty{30}{\micro\Molar} and displayed as $\pm$ their standard deviation:

\begin{itemize} \item NS9283: 3.212 $\pm$ 0.55 \item Comp-1: 1.98 $\pm$ 0.12 \item Comp-2: 2.34 $\pm$ 0.44 \item Comp-3: 1.40 $\pm$ 0.01 \item Comp-4: 3.4 $\pm$ 0.85 \item Comp-5: 2.23 $\pm$ 0.21 \item Comp-6: 2.09 $\pm$ 0.14 \item Comp-7: 1.64 $\pm$ 0.43 \item Comp-8: 1.50 $\pm$ 0.03 \item Comp-9: 2.22 $\pm$ 0.19 \item Comp-10: 2.67 $\pm$ 0.45 \item Comp-11: 1.56 $\pm$ 0.12 \item Comp-12: 1.77 $\pm$ 0.95 \item Comp-13: 1.99 $\pm$ 0.11 \item Comp-14: 1.82 $\pm$ 0.09 \item Comp-15: 2.16 $\pm$ 0.12 \item Comp-16: 2.23 $\pm$ 0.36 \item Comp-17: 1.01 $\pm$ 0.17 \item Comp-18: 0.89 $\pm$ 0.21 \item Comp-19: 0.90 $\pm$ 0.18 \item Comp-20: 2.57 $\pm$ 0.42 \item Comp-21: 2.29 $\pm$ 0.50 \item Comp-22: 0.96 $\pm$ 0.25 \item Comp-23: 1.52 $\pm$ 0.40 \item Comp-24: 0.82 $\pm$ 0.35 \item Comp-25: 1.30 $\pm$ 0.30 \item Comp-26: 1.37 $\pm$ 0.35 \end{itemize}
Question: With the data presented:

\\begin{itemize} 

\\item Provide a synthesis route for the given analogues, showing all steps/reagents

\\item Summarize the SAR implications of the screening.

\\item Why does Comp-4 (NO₂ substituent) show higher normalized ACh response than NS9283 (C≡N)?

\\end{itemize}

Think step by step and solve the problem below. In your answer, you should include all intermediate derivations, formulas, important steps, and justifications for how you arrived at your answer. Be as detailed as possible in your response.
